The Theory of Relativity, proposed by Albert Einstein, consists of two main parts: Special Relativity and General Relativity.

1. Special Relativity (1905) - This theory explains the behavior of objects at constant velocity relative to each other and in the absence of a gravitational field. It is composed of two main postulates:

- The Principle of Relativity: The laws of physics are the same for all observers in uniform motion relative to each other. This means that the laws of physics are the same whether you are standing still or moving at a constant velocity.
- The Principle of the Constant Speed of Light: The speed of light in a vacuum is constant, regardless of the motion of the observer or the source of light. That is, c = 299,792,458 m/s.

From these two postulates, several effects were derived, including time dilation, length contraction, and relativistic mass increase, which conflicted with the classical view of the relationship between space, time, and motion.

2. General Relativity (1915) - This more extensive theory explains the behavior of objects in the presence of a gravitational field. It is based on the principle that theForce of gravity is a consequence of the curvature of space and time around massive objects, caused by their energy and momentum.

In this theory, Einstein introduced the concept of a gravitational field equation, known as the Einstein Field Equations, which describes how matter and energy influence the curvature of space and time. This equation is represented as:

G_{\mu\nu} = 8 \pi T_{\mu\nu}

Where G_{\mu\nu} is the Einstein Tensor, representing the curvature of space and time, T_{\mu\nu} is the Energy-Momentum Tensor, which describes the distribution and behavior of matter and energy, and 8 \pi is a constant that relates the gravitational and inertial masses.

General Relativity has been confirmed through numerous experimental tests and is currently the most accurate theory of gravitation known. It has led to discoveries such as black holes, gravitational waves, and the expanding universe, and continues to be an active area of research in physics today.
